Using Convenience Store Point Cards: Ubiquitous Pitfall

December 21, 2017    Point card Gifts Rewards Business

This morning in the convenience store, I was a bit confused to get additional items than of I’ve had put in the basket. After paying the bill, I procrastinated too much to take the bag at the cashier counter. With the benefit of hindsight, I wondered that may have been an error, but the cashier (she) confidently has insisted that it’s mine. I still was reluctant to take it. And finally, smiling, she kindly explained in clear terms the reason why all packed items belong to me. My bag has been inflated with extra items because of the loyalty program that emphasizes on the regular usage of the point card. After figuring out her explanations, I was both happy and surprised at the same to receive an estimated gift of 620 JPY (Japanese yen) while I only had 173 points on my card.

Honestly, I ignore the commercial policy behind this motivation of granting this amount of money to me. I try to guess how many people like me have also received some gifts. I almost spent a half hour guessing the method they used to evaluate this gift but I couldn’t find a compelling response. As a conclusion to this riddle, I personally assume that it may be the fact I’ve bought particular products that have some higher weights in point calculation.

However, the dataset of point card and purchase can be used to derive insights for taking crucial decisions. In case of bad analytics, this can cause considerable loss of gifts and rewards.

For example, a given company would like to offer some discounts and rewards to thousands of clients based on purchase behavior over the last three years. Especially, those who have generated at least $5 of revenues in a rarely-bought-products in every national holiday or promotion. All of them must hold a point card that gains at least two hundred and twenty-five (250) points quarterly.

Condition: in case the same clients never missed up to buy during Christmas promotions, their rewards will increase by 3% than those never purchased one of the product couples (A, B) on weekends. In this sense, if the machine learning technique is not well tuned, this could result in a bad prediction capable of causing losses and jeopardizing the business focuses.
